<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<subsection xml:id="density" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Probability Density</title>
  <p>
    Throughout our discussion of the Normal distribution, there is one important idea that has been deliberately simplified. 
    Many introductory statistics books either avoid it completely or introduce it only briefly because it can seem counterintuitive 
    at first. Fortunately, it is not essential for carrying out most statistical analyses in R-Instat, 
    but understanding the basic idea will help you correctly interpret the results produced by the <em>Show Model</em> dialog.
  </p>
  <p>
    You may already have noticed that the graphs of the Normal distribution have the vertical axis labelled <em>Probability Density</em> 
    rather than <em>Probability</em>. You may also have used the <em>Show Model</em> dialog with the Normal 
    distribution and found that the calculated density at a particular value can sometimes be greater than one. 
    For example, if the Mean is <m>1</m> and the Standard Deviation is <m>0.1</m>, 
    the density at <m>x = 1</m> is approximately <m>3.99</m>. If you view the generated R code, you will see that 
    R-Instat performs this calculation using the <c>dnorm()</c> function.
  </p>
  <p>
    At first this result may seem surprising. Since probabilities can never be greater than one, how can the value be 3.99? 
    The answer is that the value returned is <em>not</em> a probability. Instead, it is the <em>probability density</em> 
    at the specified point.
  </p>
  <p>
    To understand why this happens, it is helpful to think about what it means for a variable to be continuous. 
    Consider the outside temperature. A thermometer may display a value of <m>23^\circ \,C</m>, but the actual temperature is rarely exactly 23. 
    It might be 23.1, 22.98 or 23.047 degrees. In reality, there are infinitely many possible values between any two temperatures. 
    The same is true for measurements such as height, weight and rainfall.
  </p>

  <p>
    Now consider what this means when discussing probabilities. Suppose tomorrow's maximum temperature follows a Normal distribution 
    with Mean <m>23</m> and Standard Deviation <m>1</m>. What is the probability that the temperature will be exactly <m>23^\circ \,C</m>? 
    The answer is essentially zero. Since there are infinitely many possible values, 
    the probability of observing one exact value is negligible. Instead, meaningful questions involve ranges of values, 
    such as the probability that the temperature lies between <m>22.5^\circ \,C</m> and <m>23.5^\circ \,C</m>, or between <m>20^\circ \,C</m> 
    and <m>30^\circ \,C</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is the key difference between discrete and continuous probability distributions. For discrete distributions, 
    such as the Binomial distribution, it is meaningful to calculate the probability of a single outcome. 
    For continuous distributions, however, probabilities are calculated over <em>intervals</em> of values rather than at individual 
    points.
  </p>

  <p>
    For continuous distributions, probabilities are represented by the <em>area under the curve</em>. 
    The total area under the entire Normal curve is always equal to one, representing a total probability of 1. 
    The probability that a value falls within a particular range is therefore equal to the area under the curve over that interval. 
    This idea was illustrated earlier in Figures <xref ref="fig-sdnorm1"/> and <xref ref="fig-sdnorm2"/>, 
    where the shaded regions represented the probability of observations falling within one or two standard deviations of the Mean.
  </p>

  <p>
    We can now return to the density values produced by the <em>Show Model</em> dialog. 
    When you request the density of a Normal distribution, R-Instat is not calculating a probability. 
    Instead, it calculates the <em>height</em> of the probability density curve at the specified value. 
    The generated R code uses the <c>dnorm()</c> function to perform this calculation. 
    Although the height of the curve is useful for describing the shape of the distribution, 
    it should not be interpreted as a probability.
  </p>

  <p>
    The density values themselves have little practical meaning when considered individually. 
    Their importance lies in ensuring that the area under the curve correctly represents probabilities. 
    In mathematical terms, the probability density function is constructed so that the total area under the curve is equal to one.
    <fn>
      Readers familiar with calculus may recognise that probability densities integrate to one over the entire range of possible values. 
      The probability that <m>X</m> lies between <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> is obtained by calculating the definite integral
      <m>\int_a^b p(x)\,dx</m>.
      If you have not studied calculus, you do not need this result to understand or use the methods presented in this book.
    </fn>
  </p>

  <p>
    In practice, when using the <em>Show Model</em> dialog in R-Instat, 
    use the <em>Probabilities</em> or <em>Quantiles</em> tabs whenever you require probabilities or probability intervals. 
    The density calculation is primarily used for displaying the shape of the distribution and for understanding how continuous 
    probability distributions behave. Remember that the density at a single point is <em>not</em> itself a probability.
  </p>

</subsection>
